Red Wine Analysis by Mark MacArdle



Dataset introduction

1599 samples of red Portuguese Vinho Verde wines.

Description of attributes:

  1. fixed acidity: most acids involved with wine or fixed or nonvolatile (do not evaporate readily)

  2. volatile acidity: the amount of acetic acid in wine, which at too high of levels can lead to an unpleasant, vinegar taste

  3. citric acid: found in small quantities, citric acid can add freshness and flavor to wines

  4. residual sugar: the amount of sugar remaining after fermentation stops, its rare to find wines with less than 1 gram/liter and wines with greater than 45 grams/liter are considered sweet

  5. chlorides: the amount of salt in the wine

  6. free sulfur dioxide: the free form of SO2 exists in equilibrium between molecular SO2 (as a dissolved gas) and bisulfite ion; it prevents microbial growth and the oxidation of wine

  7. total sulfur dioxide: amount of free and bound forms of S02; in low concentrations, SO2 is mostly undetectable in wine, but at free SO2 concentrations over 50 ppm, SO2 becomes evident in the nose and taste of wine

  8. density: the density of water is close to that of water depending on the percent alcohol and sugar content

  9. pH: describes how acidic or basic a wine is on a scale from 0 (very acidic) to 14 (very basic); most wines are between 3-4 on the pH scale

  10. sulphates: a wine additive which can contribute to sulfur dioxide gas (S02) levels, wich acts as an antimicrobial and antioxidant

  11. alcohol: the percent alcohol content of the wine


Output variable (based on sensory data):

  1. quality (score between 0 and 10). Median of at least 3 evaluations made by wine experts.


Units:

  1. Fixed acidity (tartaric acid - g / dm^3)

  2. volatile acidity (acetic acid - g / dm^3)

  3. citric acid (g / dm^3)

  4. residual sugar (g / dm^3)

  5. chlorides (sodium chloride - g / dm^3)

  6. free sulfur dioxide (mg / dm^3)

  7. total sulfur dioxide (mg / dm^3)

  8. density (g / cm^3)

  9. pH

  10. sulphates (potassium sulphate - g / dm3)

  11. alcohol (% by volume)

  12. quality (score between 0 and 10)

Univariate Plots Section

Quality

  • 1 to 10 scale actual values are only between 3 and 8.
  • Peak at 5 and 6. Makes sense as mean on a 1 to 10 scale would be 5.5
  • Looks like there may be more wines above 5.5 than below.

This graph looks normally distributed, with a little positive skew as it looks like theres a longer tail on the right of the graph. This makes sense as the quality scores are the median of at least 3 expert reviews. From the cental limit therom we can should expect to see a normal distribution, even if all the individual scores plotted a different distribution.

Creating a box plot to investigate further as I want to see the quartile ranges better. Overlaid a points plot get a better idea of the densities.

  • Wines scoring 3 and 8 are identified as outliers.
  • The median line cant be seen as its at 6, on top of the 3rd quartile line.



Alcohol

  • Positively skewed distribution.
  • Big peak at 9.5% and some other, smaller peaks at 10.5 and 11%. This is likely from a tendency to make alcohol levels to round numbers for marketing.



Density

  • Normally distributed
  • Very small range.



Acidity related variables

This is fixed.acidity, volatile.acidity, citric.acid and pH

  • fixed.acidity, volatile.acidity and citric.acid all positively skewed.
  • volatile acidity has a bimodal distribution with peaks at roughly 0.42 and 0.58.
  • citric.acid has an spike at just below 0.5.
  • pH is normally distributed

I find it surprising that pH is normally distributed given the other acid variables are all skewed to lower levels. I expected pH would have been skewed towards more neutral (towards 7) with a long tail to lower pH values.

To investigate this further Im creating a new variable that sums the 3 acid variables. They measure tartaric, acetic and citric acids and all have the same units of g/litre so can be added together without modification.

This will hopefully give a rough guide to total acidity but may be flawed if the three acids have very different strengths.

wine$total.acids <- with(wine, fixed.acidity + volatile.acidity + citric.acid)

  • Distibution is still a bit positively skewed.



Sulphate and Sulpher Variables

  • All 3 are skewed to the right.

Total.sulfur.dioxide is the very skewed so may benefit from a log transformation

This gives a much more normal distribution which may be useful in later analysis.



Salt and Sugar (chlorides and residual.sugar variables)

Looking at chlorides (which is the salt content) and residual.sugar variables together as these are two things that are normally labelled as bad for your health.

  • similar distributions: big peaks low in the range and then a few much higher outliers.

In the bivariate analysis section Ill investigate if its the same wines that have both high salt and sugar or if its more random.

1599 observations of 11 input variables, which are all numeric, and one output variable for quality which is between 1 and 10.

The main feature of interest is quality. I want to look at what other variables influence this and if a predictive model can be made from them.

What other features in the dataset do you think will help support your

investigation into your feature(s) of interest?

I expect alcohol to have an effect on quality but its hard to know intuitively how the other variables will affect it. Correclations can be measured to gauge which are the most important though.

Did you create any new variables from existing variables in the dataset?

Added total.acids to help investigate why pH is normally distibuted while the 3 different acids measured are all skewed to low levels. It will be interesting to look at the relationship of this new variable to pH in the bivariate section.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions?

Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the

form of the data? If so, why did you do this?

Citric.acid was unusual having a high spike at just below 0.5 and being fairly flat for most of its distribution.

I was surprised to see that pH and density had normal distributions given that the variables that I expected to inflence them (fixed.acidity, volatile acidity and citric acid for pH and alcohol and residual.sugar for density) all had skewed distributions.

Quality Vs Alcohol

In the graph jitter has been added horizontally but not vertically.

  • The linear regression line shows a trend between increasing alcohol and increasing quality.
  • The lowest alcohol content for wine with quality=8 is 9.5%. This looks to be above the median of the quality=5 wines. A boxplot chart may illustrate this better.
  • The highest alcohol content off the quality=3 wines is 11%. This looks close median of the quality=6 wines and below that of the quality=7 wines. Again a boxplot would better visualise this.
  • There seems to be an odd lower cutoff of alcohol point for the quality= 4, 5 and 6 wines of 9%. Theres a couple of outliers below this but it seems odd they stop so suddenly.
  • There looks to be a gap between wines at or near 13.5% and 14% percent. As theres a few wines on exactly 14% maybe theres a marketing reason makers aim for this.
  • Theres an outlier at nearly 15% alcohol for quality=5 and quality=4 also has a high indvidual outlier at just over 13%.

Remaking the graph as a boxplot.

  • Theres a lot of outliers in quality=5

  • The interquartile ranges for quality = 4, 6, 7, 8 are similar. Its odd that quality=5 has such a small range with so many outliers.

Alcohol Vs volatile.acidity

As these two variables have the highest correlations with quality it is worth seeing if they have a correlation with each other. If they have a strong correlation to each other that would imply theyre explaining the same part of qualitys variation. It would be more interesting if they realatively independent as then they can be used to explain more of variation in quality and would allow for better prediction of it.

Other Acidity Variables

Using ggpairs on just the acidity and quality variables.

The very linear scatterplot between fixed.acidity and total.acids stands out and highlights something I hadnt realised when I made the total.acids variable. The range of fixed.acidity is far greater than volatile.acidity or citric acid. Due to this total.acids is nearly equal to fixed.acidity. Their correlation is also nearly perfect at 0.996 which futher illustrates this point.

This makes total.acids irrelevant as fixed.acidity can be used in its place.

What would may be more useful is if total.acids was change to sum of normalised acids. The 3 acid variables divided by their ranges.

#normalise each variable by dividing by its range (max - min)
wine$total.acids <- with(wine, 
                         fixed.acidity / 
                           (max(fixed.acidity ) - min(fixed.acidity))
                         +
                           volatile.acidity / 
                           (max(volatile.acidity) - min(volatile.acidity)) 
                         +
                           citric.acid / 
                           (max(citric.acid) - min(citric.acid)))

#```{r echo=FALSE, message=FALSE, warning=FALSE}
ggpairs(wine[, c("fixed.acidity", "volatile.acidity", "citric.acid", 
                 "pH", "total.acids", "quality")])

total.acid is now a more interesting variable. It shows a high correlation with both fixed.acidity and citric.acid but not volatile.acidity. Its interesting that volatile.acidity doesnt move with the other two.

Unfortunately total.acids correlation to pH is lower than fixed.acidity and its correlation to quality is lower than the 4 other acid variables so Im not sure if Ill use it any further.

Below the relationship between fixed.acidity and pH is shown. The relationship betweent the two isnt great and doesnt fit a curving or linear line that well.

Citric acid has a small relationship with quality and may be useful when modelling it.

  • Theres an odd gap in quality=7 and 8 values of citric acid around 0.25. I dont know what could be the cause of this.



Sulphate and Sulpher Variables

  • Although still small sulphates has the higest correlation to quality
  • Only total and free.sulfur.dioxide have a high correlation to each other here.

The difference between free and total sulfur dioxide is bound sulfur dioxide. I wonder if a variable for this might yield any more information.

The bound.sulfur.dioxide has a higher correlation with quality and an even lower correlation with sulphates. Although bound SO2 and sulphates only have low correlations with quality, the fact they dont correlate well with each other suggests they explain different parts to the variation in quality. This will be useful when making a model for quality.

Bivariate Analysis

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the

investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features

in the dataset?

Alcohol and volatile.acidity had the strongest correlations to quality. Alcohols relationship was positive and volatile.aciditys negative.

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features

(not the main feature(s) of interest)?

Bound.sulfur.dioxide and sulphates both have a small relationship with quality but not with each other. This may make them useful for explaining different parts of qualitys variation in a model.

What was the strongest relationship you found?

I created a new variable called total.acid which was the sum of the three acid variables. It had a near perfect correlation to fixed.acidity and that helped me realise an oversight. Fixed.acidity is much bigger in magnitude than the other two acidity variables so when I summed them it accounted for nearly all the variation.

Due to this I modified the variable to be a sum of the 3 other variables normalised.

Aside from this pH and fixed.acidity had a high relationship of 0.68 which makes sense as they are two difference measures of acidity.

Building a Linear Model

Showing the r code below so that its visible what variables are added to each model.

m1 <- lm(quality ~ alcohol, data = wine)
m2 <- update(m1, ~ . + volatile.acidity)
m3 <- update(m2, ~ . + sulphates)
m4 <- update(m3, ~ . + bound.sulfur.dioxide)

#add all the other variables to a 5th variable just to see if it helps
m5 <- update(m4, ~ . + fixed.acidity + citric.acid + residual.sugar + chlorides +
               free.sulfur.dioxide + total.sulfur.dioxide + density + pH)

#need to have memisc library installed and loaded for mtable to work.
mtable(m1, m2, m3, m4, m5, sdigits = 3)

Final Plots and Summary

Plot One

Description One

From quality=5 to 8 it can be seen how the mean alcohol is increasing and the mean volatile acidity decreasing. These are the strongest correlating variables to quality.



Plot Two

Description Two

The line between the mean points shows an interesting relationship. Bound SO2 and quality dont have a linear relationship. Theres a peak at quality=5. This shows that increasing bound SO2 is initally benificial but then a hindrence to reaching high quality levels. Whereas increasing sulphates has a more linear relationship with higher levels correlating with higher quality scores.



Plot Three

Description Three

It is interesting that there are no wines that are high in both salt and sugar. This was unexpected as its common for other drinks to contain high levels of both to improve their taste.

It can be seen that quality=5 are the most common high salt wine, qualit=6 are most common high sugar wines but the vast majority of wines are clustered with both low salt and sugar.



Reflection

It was interesting that alcohol percentage had the strongest correlation to quality of the variables. The strenght of a wine is rarely discussed as key component of how good it will taste. The fact it had the strongest correlation may point to a basic fact that connoisseurs see as beneath them: that people often just like alcohol.

I stuggled to create an new variables that had a strong correlation to quality. Bound.sulfur.dioxide was the best I did and it did have some limited use.

I was surprised that the acidity variables didnt have much correlation to the pH. It seemed natural to think that they woudl have been what was driving the pH.

I was also surprised that salt and sugar didnt have a correlation to quality or each other as they are so commonly used to improve the taste in other drinks.

Future work could be done on investigating non linear modelling methods that could be used to make better predicitons of quality from the input variables.
